Text: DOLE: Thank you very much, Jim.
Speech: Thank you very much, Jim.
Speaker: DOLE
Name: Robert J. Dole

Text: Let me first give you a sports update.
Speech: Let me first give you a sports update.
Speaker: DOLE
Name: Robert J. Dole

Text: The Braves, one; the Cardinals, nothing, early on.
Speech: The Braves, one; the Cardinals, nothing, early on.
Speaker: DOLE
Name: Robert J. Dole

Text: I want to thank you and I want to thank everybody here tonight.
Speech: I want to thank you and I want to thank everybody here tonight.
Speaker: DOLE
Name: Robert J. Dole

Text: I want to give a special thanks to my wife Elizabeth, my daughter Robin for their love and support, and thank the people who are listening and watching all over America.
Speech: I want to give a special thanks to my wife Elizabeth, my daughter Robin for their love and support, and thank the people who are listening and watching all over America.
Speaker: DOLE
Name: Robert J. Dole

Text: In 20 days, you will help decide who will lead this country into the next century.
Speech: In 20 days, you will help decide who will lead this country into the next century.
Speaker: DOLE
Name: Robert J. Dole

Text: It's an awesome responsibility.
Speech: It's an awesome responsibility.
Speaker: DOLE
Name: Robert J. Dole

Text: And you must ask yourself, do you know enough about the candidates?
Speech: And you must ask yourself, do you know enough about the candidates?
Speaker: DOLE
Name: Robert J. Dole

Text: You should know as much as possible about each of us.
Speech: You should know as much as possible about each of us.
Speaker: DOLE
Name: Robert J. Dole

Text: Sometimes the views have been distorted.
Speech: Sometimes the views have been distorted.

Name: Robert J. Dole

Text: There's been millions and millions of dollars of negative advertising spent distorting my views.
Speech: There's been millions and millions of dollars of negative advertising spent distorting my views.
Speaker: DOLE
Name: Robert J. Dole

Text: But I hope tonight you will get a better feel of who Bob Dole is and what he's all about.
Speech: But I hope tonight you will get a better feel of who Bob Dole is and what he's all about.
Speaker: DOLE
Name: Robert J. Dole

Text: And I think first you should -- I should understand that the question on your mind is do I understand your problem.
Speech: And I think first you should -- I should understand that the question on your mind is do I understand your problem.
Speaker: DOLE
Name: Robert J. Dole

Text: Would I understand it if it occurred to me, and I might just say I'm from a large family.
Speech: Would I understand it if it occurred to me, and I might just say I'm from a large family.
Speaker: DOLE
Name: Robert J. Dole

Text: I got lots of relatives and they're good, average, middle-class, hardworking Americans.
Speech: I got lots of relatives and they're good, average, middle-class, hardworking Americans.

Name: Robert J. Dole

Text: They live all across the country.
Speech: They live all across the country.

Name: Robert J. Dole

Text: They're not all Republicans.
Speech: They're not all Republicans.

Name: Robert J. Dole

Text: Maybe all but one.
Speech: Maybe all but one.
Speaker: DOLE
Name: Robert J. Dole

Text: But in any event, I understand the problems.
Speech: But in any event, I understand the problems.
Speaker: DOLE
Name: Robert J. Dole

Text: Whether it's two parents working because one has to pay the taxes and one has to provide for the family, whether it's a single parent who just barely pays the pressing bills or whether you're worried about an education for your children going to the best schools, or whether you're worried about safe playgrounds, drug-free schools, crime-free schools.
Speech: Whether it's two parents working because one has to pay the taxes and one has to provide for the family, whether it's a single parent who just barely pays the pressing bills or whether you're worried about an education for your children going to the best schools, or whether you're worried about safe playgrounds, drug-free schools, crime-free schools.

Name: Robert J. Dole

Text: This is what this election is all about.
Speech: This is what this election is all about.
Speaker: DOLE
Name: Robert J. Dole

Text: And hopefully tonight when we conclude this debate you will have a better understanding and the viewing and listening audience will have a better understanding.
Speech: And hopefully tonight when we conclude this debate you will have a better understanding and the viewing and listening audience will have a better understanding.
Speaker: DOLE
Name: Robert J. Dole

Text: CLINTON: I was going to applaud, too.
Speech: I was going to applaud, too.

Name: William(Bill) J. Clinton

Text: Well, thank you, Jim.
Speech: Well, thank you, Jim.
Speaker: CLINTON
Name: William(Bill) J. Clinton

Text: And thanks to the people of San Diego for giving us this opportunity to have another discussion about the decision we all face in front of people who will make the decision.
Speech: And thanks to the people of San Diego for giving us this opportunity to have another discussion about the decision we all face in front of people who will make the decision.
Speaker: CLINTON
Name: William(Bill) J. Clinton

Text: Again, I will say I will do my best to make this a discussion of ideas and issues, not insults.
Speech: Again, I will say I will do my best to make this a discussion of ideas and issues, not insults.
Speaker: CLINTON
Name: William(Bill) J. Clinton

Text: What really matters is what happens to your future and what happens to our country as we stand on the brink of a new century, a time of extraordinary possibility.
Speech: What really matters is what happens to your future and what happens to our country as we stand on the brink of a new century, a time of extraordinary possibility.
Speaker: CLINTON
Name: William(Bill) J. Clinton

Text: I have a simple philosophy that I tried to follow for the last four years: Do what creates opportunity for all, what reinforces responsibility from all of us, and what will help us build a community where everybody's got a role to play and a place at the table.
Speech: I have a simple philosophy that I tried to follow for the last four years: Do what creates opportunity for all, what reinforces responsibility from all of us, and what will help us build a community where everybody's got a role to play and a place at the table.
Speaker: CLINTON
Name: William(Bill) J. Clinton

Text: Compared to four years ago, we're clearly better off.
Speech: Compared to four years ago, we're clearly better off.
Speaker: CLINTON
Name: William(Bill) J. Clinton

Text: We've got ten and a half million more jobs, the deficit's been reduced by 60 percent.
Speech: We've got ten and a half million more jobs, the deficit's been reduced by 60 percent.
Speaker: CLINTON
Name: William(Bill) J. Clinton

Text: Incomes are rising for the first time in a decade, the crime rates, the welfare rolls are falling, we're putting , 100,000 more police on the street.
Speech: Incomes are rising for the first time in a decade, the crime rates, the welfare rolls are falling, we're putting , 100,000 more police on the street.

Speech: 60,000 felons, fugitives and stalkers have been denied handguns.

Name: William(Bill) J. Clinton

Text: But that progress is only the beginning.
Speech: But that progress is only the beginning.
Speaker: CLINTON
Name: William(Bill) J. Clinton

Text: What we really should focus on tonight is what we still have to do to help the American people make the most of this future that's out there.
Speech: What we really should focus on tonight is what we still have to do to help the American people make the most of this future that's out there.
Speaker: CLINTON
Name: William(Bill) J. Clinton

Text: I think what really matters is what we can do to build strong families.
Speech: I think what really matters is what we can do to build strong families.
Speaker: CLINTON
Name: William(Bill) J. Clinton

Text: Strong families need a strong economy.
Speech: Strong families need a strong economy.
Speaker: CLINTON
Name: William(Bill) J. Clinton

Text: To me that means we have to go on and balance this budget while we protect Medicare and Medicaid and education and the environment.
Speech: To me that means we have to go on and balance this budget while we protect Medicare and Medicaid and education and the environment.
Speaker: CLINTON
Name: William(Bill) J. Clinton

Text: We should give a tax cut, targeted to child rearing and education, to buying a first home and paying for health care.
Speech: We should give a tax cut, targeted to child rearing and education, to buying a first home and paying for health care.
Speaker: CLINTON
Name: William(Bill) J. Clinton

Text: We ought to help protect our kids from drugs and guns and gangs and tobacco.
Speech: We ought to help protect our kids from drugs and guns and gangs and tobacco.
Speaker: CLINTON
Name: William(Bill) J. Clinton

Text: We ought to help move a million people from welfare to work and we ought to create the finest education system in the world where every 18-year-old can go on to college and all of our younger children have great educational opportunities.
Speech: We ought to help move a million people from welfare to work and we ought to create the finest education system in the world where every 18-year-old can go on to college and all of our younger children have great educational opportunities.
Speaker: CLINTON
Name: William(Bill) J. Clinton

Text: If we do those things, we can build that bridge to the 21st century.
Speech: If we do those things, we can build that bridge to the 21st century.
Speaker: CLINTON
Name: William(Bill) J. Clinton

Text: That's what I hope to get to talk about tonight.
Speech: That's what I hope to get to talk about tonight.
Speaker: CLINTON
Name: William(Bill) J. Clinton

Text: And I think what we'll plainly do is what we did in 1983 when Senator Dole served, and this is something I think he did a good job on when he served on the Social Security commission and they made some modest changes in Social Security to make sure that it would be alive and well into the 21st century.

Speaker: DOLE
Name: Robert J. Dole

Text: Maybe we will have another debate on the economy.
Speech: Maybe we will have another debate on the economy.
Speaker: DOLE
Name: Robert J. Dole

Text: But I would just say this.
Speech: But I would just say this.
Speaker: DOLE
Name: Robert J. Dole

Text: This is the highest honor that I have ever had in my life, to think that somebody from Russell, Kansas, somebody who grew up living in a basement apartment, someone whose parents didn't finish high school, somebody who spent about 39 months in hospitals after World War II, someone who uses a buttonhook every day to get dressed.
Speech: This is the highest honor that I have ever had in my life, to think that somebody from Russell, Kansas, somebody who grew up living in a basement apartment, someone whose parents didn't finish high school, somebody who spent about 39 months in hospitals after World War II, someone who uses a buttonhook every day to get dressed.
Speaker: DOLE
Name: Robert J. Dole

Text: Somebody who understands that there're real Americans out there with real problems, whether soccer moms, or the single parents, the families or the seniors, or people with disabilities, whoever it may be.
Speech: Somebody who understands that there're real Americans out there with real problems, whether soccer moms, or the single parents, the families or the seniors, or people with disabilities, whoever it may be.
Speaker: DOLE
Name: Robert J. Dole

Text: There are some very fundamental differences in this campaign.
Speech: There are some very fundamental differences in this campaign.
Speaker: DOLE
Name: Robert J. Dole

Text: President Clinton opposes term limits, President Clinton opposes a constitutional amendment to balance the budget.
Speech: President Clinton opposes term limits, President Clinton opposes a constitutional amendment to balance the budget.
Speaker: DOLE
Name: Robert J. Dole

Text: President Clinton opposes voluntary prayer amendment.
Speech: President Clinton opposes voluntary prayer amendment.
Speaker: DOLE
Name: Robert J. Dole

Text: Opposes an amendment to protect the flag of the United States of America.
Speech: Opposes an amendment to protect the flag of the United States of America.
Speaker: DOLE
Name: Robert J. Dole

Text: People give their lives.
Speech: People give their lives.
Speaker: DOLE
Name: Robert J. Dole

Text: Couple of service men here.
Speech: Couple of service men here.
Speaker: DOLE
Name: Robert J. Dole

Text: They sacrifice, they give everything for America.
Speech: They sacrifice, they give everything for America.
Speaker: DOLE
Name: Robert J. Dole

Text: We ought to protect the American flag with a constitutional amendment.
Speech: We ought to protect the American flag with a constitutional amendment.
Speaker: DOLE
Name: Robert J. Dole

Text: But beyond that we need to address the economy.
Speech: But beyond that we need to address the economy.
Speaker: DOLE
Name: Robert J. Dole

Text: I will just say my time is running out here.
Speech: I will just say my time is running out here.
Speaker: DOLE
Name: Robert J. Dole

Text: It's a very proud moment for me.
Speech: It's a very proud moment for me.
Speaker: DOLE
Name: Robert J. Dole

Text: What I want the voters to do is to make a decision.
Speech: What I want the voters to do is to make a decision.
Speaker: DOLE
Name: Robert J. Dole

Text: And I want them to be proud of their vote in the years ahead.
Speech: And I want them to be proud of their vote in the years ahead.
Speaker: DOLE
Name: Robert J. Dole

Text: Proud that they voted for the right candidate.
Speech: Proud that they voted for the right candidate.
Speaker: DOLE
Name: Robert J. Dole

Text: Proud that they voted hopefully for me.
Speech: Proud that they voted hopefully for me.
Speaker: DOLE
Name: Robert J. Dole

Text: And I'll just make you one promise, my word is good.
Speech: And I'll just make you one promise, my word is good.
Speaker: DOLE
Name: Robert J. Dole

Text: Democrats and Republicans said Bob Dole's word is good.
Speech: Democrats and Republicans said Bob Dole's word is good.
Speaker: DOLE
Name: Robert J. Dole

Text: I keep my word.
Speech: I keep my word.
Speaker: DOLE
Name: Robert J. Dole

Text: I promise you the economy is going to get better.
Speech: I promise you the economy is going to get better.
Speaker: DOLE
Name: Robert J. Dole

Text: We're going to have a good economic package.
Speech: We're going to have a good economic package.
Speaker: DOLE
Name: Robert J. Dole

Text: We're going into the next century a better America.
Speech: We're going into the next century a better America.
Speaker: DOLE
Name: Robert J. Dole

Text: CLINTON: Thank you, Jim.
Speech: Thank you, Jim.
Speaker: CLINTON
Name: William(Bill) J. Clinton

Text: And thank you, ladies and gentlemen, and all the people who are watching.
Speech: And thank you, ladies and gentlemen, and all the people who are watching.
Speaker: CLINTON
Name: William(Bill) J. Clinton

Text: One thing I would like to say is I agree with what Senator Dole said.
Speech: One thing I would like to say is I agree with what Senator Dole said.
Speaker: CLINTON
Name: William(Bill) J. Clinton

Text: It's a remarkable thing in a country like ours, a man who grew up in Russell, Kansas, and one who was born to a widowed mother in Hope, Arkansas, could wind up running for president.
Speech: It's a remarkable thing in a country like ours, a man who grew up in Russell, Kansas, and one who was born to a widowed mother in Hope, Arkansas, could wind up running for president.
Speaker: CLINTON
Name: William(Bill) J. Clinton

Text: Could have a chance to serve as president.
Speech: Could have a chance to serve as president.
Speaker: CLINTON
Name: William(Bill) J. Clinton

Text: First thing I want to say is thank you for giving me the chance to be president.
Speech: First thing I want to say is thank you for giving me the chance to be president.
Speaker: CLINTON
Name: William(Bill) J. Clinton

Text: This election is about two different visions about how we should go into the 21st Century.
Speech: This election is about two different visions about how we should go into the 21st Century.
Speaker: CLINTON
Name: William(Bill) J. Clinton

Text: Would we be better off as I believe, working together to give each other the tools we need to make the most of our God-given potential, or are we better off saying, you're on your own?
Speech: Would we be better off as I believe, working together to give each other the tools we need to make the most of our God-given potential, or are we better off saying, you're on your own?
Speaker: CLINTON
Name: William(Bill) J. Clinton

Text: Would we be better off building that bridge to the future together so we can all walk across it or saying you can get across yourself?
Speech: Would we be better off building that bridge to the future together so we can all walk across it or saying you can get across yourself?
Speaker: CLINTON
Name: William(Bill) J. Clinton

Text: If you don't agree -- leave this room with anything else tonight and if the people watching us don't leave with anything else, I hope you will leave with this.
Speech: If you don't agree -- leave this room with anything else tonight and if the people watching us don't leave with anything else, I hope you will leave with this.
Speaker: CLINTON
Name: William(Bill) J. Clinton

Text: This is a real important election.
Speech: This is a real important election.
Speaker: CLINTON
Name: William(Bill) J. Clinton

Text: The world is changing dramatically in how we work and how we live, how we relate to each other, huge changes.
Speech: The world is changing dramatically in how we work and how we live, how we relate to each other, huge changes.
Speaker: CLINTON
Name: William(Bill) J. Clinton

Text: And the decisions we make will have enormous practical consequences.
Speech: And the decisions we make will have enormous practical consequences.
Speaker: CLINTON
Name: William(Bill) J. Clinton

Text: So we've talked about our responsibility tonight.
Speech: So we've talked about our responsibility tonight.
Speaker: CLINTON
Name: William(Bill) J. Clinton

Text: I want to talk about your responsibility, and your responsibility.
Speech: I want to talk about your responsibility, and your responsibility.
Speaker: CLINTON
Name: William(Bill) J. Clinton

Text: Your responsibility is to show up on November the 5th.
Speech: Your responsibility is to show up on November the 5th.
Speaker: CLINTON
Name: William(Bill) J. Clinton

Text: Because you're going to decide whether we're going to balance the budget now, but protect Medicare, Medicaid, education and the environment.
Speech: Because you're going to decide whether we're going to balance the budget now, but protect Medicare, Medicaid, education and the environment.
Speaker: CLINTON
Name: William(Bill) J. Clinton

Text: You will decide whether we're going to keep fighting crime with a Brady Bill, assault weapons and finish putting those 100,000 police.
Speech: You will decide whether we're going to keep fighting crime with a Brady Bill, assault weapons and finish putting those 100,000 police.
Speaker: CLINTON
Name: William(Bill) J. Clinton

Text: Whether we're going to move a million people from welfare to work.
Speech: Whether we're going to move a million people from welfare to work.
Speaker: CLINTON
Name: William(Bill) J. Clinton

Text: Whether we're going to give our families more protection for their kids against drugs and tobacco and gangs and guns.
Speech: Whether we're going to give our families more protection for their kids against drugs and tobacco and gangs and guns.
Speaker: CLINTON
Name: William(Bill) J. Clinton

Text: Whether we're going to give our children a world-class education.
Speech: Whether we're going to give our children a world-class education.
Speaker: CLINTON
Name: William(Bill) J. Clinton

Text: Where every eight-year-old can read.
Speech: Where every eight-year-old can read.
Speaker: CLINTON
Name: William(Bill) J. Clinton

Text: Every 12-year-old can log in on the Internet.
Speech: Every 12-year-old can log in on the Internet.
Speaker: CLINTON
Name: William(Bill) J. Clinton

Text: Every 18-year-old can go to college.
Speech: Every 18-year-old can go to college.
Speaker: CLINTON
Name: William(Bill) J. Clinton

Text: If we do those things we will build that bridge to the 21st Century and the greatest country in history will be even greater.
Speech: If we do those things we will build that bridge to the 21st Century and the greatest country in history will be even greater.
Speaker: CLINTON
Name: William(Bill) J. Clinton
